fields.label: Organization Name
fields.help_context: An organization name is a non-personal name that refers to a structured body of one or more persons that exists to perform some common function.

fields.label: Address 1
fields.help_context: Address Line 1 is generally for the civic number and street name (street address).

fields.label: Address 2
fields.help_context: Address Line 2 is for the apartment, suite, unit number, or other address designation that is not part of the physical address.

fields.label: City
fields.help_context: Address Line 3 is typically for the city.

fields.label: Country
fields.help_context: Address Line 4 is typically for the country.

fields.label: Organization Levels
fields.help_context: An organizational levelis a layer in a hierarchical order that is representative of the structure of your firm.

fields.label: Organization Indicators
fields.help_context: Measuring organizational performance. One of the most useful indicators of organizational effectiveness is how well an organization meets its goals.

fields.label: Start Limit
fields.help_context: Indicators start limit of the respective organization.

fields.label: End Limit
fields.help_context: Indicators End limit of the respective organization.

fields.label: Hierarchy Level
fields.help_context: The levels of hierarchy refer to the number of layers within an organisation. Traditional organisations were tall with many layers of hierarchy and were often authoritarian in nature.

fields.label: Hierarchy Name
fields.help_context: A hierarchical name reflects a user's or server's place in the hierarchy and controls whether users and servers in different organizations and organizational units can communicate with each another.

fields.label: Fiscal Year Start
fields.help_context: A Fiscal Year (FY), also known as a budget year, is a period of time used by the government and businesses for accounting purposes to formulate annual financial statements and reports. A fiscal year consists of 12 months or 52 weeks and might not end on December 31.

fields.label: Week Start
fields.help_context: The first day of the week. Choose which day to start the week.

fields.label: Logo
fields.help_context: A Printed symbol or design that a company or an organization uses as its special sign.

fields.label: Reporting Currency
fields.help_context: Reporting currency is the currency in which an entity's financial statements or other financial documents are reported. Choosing one currency for reporting makes it easier to understand the financial documents across the board.

fields.label: Number Format-Decimals
fields.help_context: DecimalFormat is a concrete subclass of NumberFormat that formats decimal numbers. Enter your designated DecimalFormat.

fields.label: Number Format-Comma Seperator
fields.help_context: NumberFormat-Comma Seperator that segrate decimal numbers with commas as seperators. Choose yes to avail this Format-Seperator.

fields.label: Functionl Level Code
fields.help_context: A functional level code is a structure that groups and defines from parent Â to its hierarchical sub-child until it runs to its very leaf.

fields.label: Parent Level ID
fields.help_context: The Parent Level Id specifies the identifier of each unique parent item in an hierarchical structure.

fields.label: Currency Code
fields.help_context: A three-character (letter) symbol of a currency according to the international ISO standard. As a rule, the first two letters denote the name of the country, and the third letter, the name of the currency thereof.

fields.label: Currency Name
fields.help_context: Currency name refers to the Name of the currency with its respective Currency code.

fields.label: Sign
fields.help_context: A currency sign or symbol is essentially a representation of the currency in its graphical form. These small symbols are there to avoid hassle and to identify the currency from a glance.

fields.label: Perspective Code
fields.help_context: This perspective code refers to uniqe identification of an inividual perspective.

fields.label: Perspective
fields.help_context: This perspective refers to internal business processes. Metrics based on this perspective allow the managers to know how well their business is running, and whether its products and services conform to customer requirements.

fields.label: Description
fields.help_context: Description refers to a descriptive definition of its respective perspectives.

fields.label: UOM Code
fields.help_context: UOM code Identifies the unique UOM values.

fields.label: Description
fields.help_context: Description refers to a descriptive definition of its respective UOM.

fields.label: Config Type
fields.help_context: Enter a relevant Config type.

fields.label: Config Code
fields.help_context: Config code for its respective config type.

fields.label: Config Value
fields.help_context: Enter a appropriate Config value.

fields.label: Chart Type
fields.help_context: "A chart is a graphical representation for data visualization, in which ""the data is represented by symbols. Please Select from about options."

fields.label: Search Attributes
fields.help_context: It is an input field through which Attributes of a particular chart can be filtered.

fields.label: Functional Hierarchy Level
fields.help_context: The levels of hierarchy refer to the number of layers within an organisation. Traditional organisations were tall with many layers of hierarchy and were often authoritarian in nature.

fields.label: Perspective /Business Goal/ KPI
fields.help_context:
The basic structure of a KPI scorecard includes four perspectives: financial, customer, internal process, and learning & growth. Each perspective is represented by a set of measurable goals or objectives. /

KPI goals are long-term performance measurements used by businesses to ensure a final objective is achieved. /

Key performance indicators (KPIs) refer to a set of quantifiable measurements used to gauge a company's overall long-term performance.

fields.label: Weight
fields.help_context: Overall Perspective weight should be equal to 100 under specific Scorecard. / Overall Objective weight should be equal to 100 under the specific Perspective. / Overall KPI weight should be equal to 100 under the specific Objective.

fields.label: Score
fields.help_context: The score is calculated using the Actual Value of the current KPI, as indicated in the specified equations.

fields.label: Action Item
fields.help_context: We initiate an Action Item when we require to overcome the score.

fields.label: Target
fields.help_context: We can set the Target Date for the Action Item.

fields.label: Target
fields.help_context: We can set the Target Date for the Action Item.

fields.label: Ownership
fields.help_context: Mention the Ownership (Admin) of the Initiative Action Item.

fields.label: Scorecard Description
fields.help_context: A KPI scorecard is a term used to describe a statistical record that measures progress or achievement towards a set performance indicator.

fields.label: From Date
fields.help_context: We can define the date ranges to use in KPI data calculations when we are creating a new scorecard using From Date.

fields.label: To Date
fields.help_context: We can define the date ranges to use in KPI data calculations when we are editing an existing scorecard using To Date.

fields.label: Perspective
fields.help_context: The basic structure of a KPI scorecard includes four perspectives: financial, customer, internal process, and learning & growth.

fields.label: Perspective Weight
fields.help_context: Measuring the total performance scores of the four perspectives (BSC) by the weight of each KPI is used in each BSC perspective.

fields.label: Objective Code
fields.help_context: Specify the Objective Code.

fields.label: Objective
fields.help_context: A balanced scorecard is a strategic management performance metric that helps companies identify and improve their internal operations to help their external outcomes.

fields.label: Objective Weight
fields.help_context: Measuring the total performance scores of the Objectives by the weight of each KPI is used in each BSC objective.

fields.label: KPI Code
fields.help_context: Specify the KPI Code.

fields.label: KPI
fields.help_context: Key performance indicators (KPIs) refer to a set of quantifiable measurements used to gauge a company's overall long-term performance.

fields.label: KPI Weight
fields.help_context: Measuring the total performance scores of each KPI.

fields.label: Frequency
fields.help_context: The KPI Frequency clarifies how often you are going to pull data from your KPI Data Source and review your performance indicators.

fields.label: Period Type
fields.help_context: Specify the Period Type as Beginning or End.

fields.label: Measure
fields.help_context: KPIs are normally numbers, percentages or units that can be measured to understand the progress of your business.

fields.label: Baseline
fields.help_context: KPI baseline indicator is when we want to continue the baseline level of achievement.

fields.label: Target
fields.help_context: A key performance indicator (KPI) can have a target, which is the exact value that the KPI should achieve.

fields.label: Minimum
fields.help_context: A key performance indicator (KPI) can have a minimum value.

fields.label: Maximum
fields.help_context: A key performance indicator (KPI) can have a maximum value.

fields.label: Optimization
fields.help_context: Specify the Optimization as minimum or maximum.

fields.label: Chart Type
fields.help_context: Select the Chart Type for the specific KPI.

fields.label: YTD
fields.help_context: Year-to-date (YTD) refers to the period of time beginning the first day of the current calendar year or fiscal year up to the current date.

fields.label: KPI Owner
fields.help_context: KPI Owner has all the rights to enter the actual values, Edit and View.

fields.label: KPI User
fields.help_context: KPI User has only the right to view the KPI Actuals.

fields.label: Indicators
fields.help_context: Measuring KPI performance. One of the most useful indicators of organizational effectiveness is how well an organization meets its goals.

fields.label: Start Limit
fields.help_context: Indicators start limit of the respective KPI.

fields.label: End Limit
fields.help_context: Indicators End limit of the respective KPI.
